<div id="review_2339193557" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2339193557" />
    <a title="Tanya Sridhar" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16852913-tanya-sridhar"><img alt="Tanya Sridhar" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1565504974p2/16852913.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2339193557?book_show_action=true">May 06, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tanya Sridhar" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tanya Sridhar" href="/user/show/16852913-tanya-sridhar">Tanya Sridhar</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/32493255-once-and-always">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16852913-tanya-sridhar?shelf=historical-romance">historical-romance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16852913-tanya-sridhar?shelf=all-aboard-the-fuck-no-train">all-aboard-the-fuck-no-train</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16852913-tanya-sridhar?shelf=cheating-or-seems-like-cheating">cheating-or-seems-like-cheating</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16852913-tanya-sridhar?shelf=severe-trigger-warning">severe-trigger-warning</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16852913-tanya-sridhar?shelf=he-hurts-me-so-it-must-be-my-fault">he-hurts-me-so-it-must-be-my-fault</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16852913-tanya-sridhar?shelf=burn-it-with-hell-fire">burn-it-with-hell-fire</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16852913-tanya-sridhar?shelf=douche-in-chief">douche-in-chief</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16852913-tanya-sridhar?shelf=hero-cheats-multiple-times">hero-cheats-multiple-times</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2339193557" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16638354384764850560">Okay. Okay. You can do this. <br/><br/><img src='https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1525630344ra/25491513.gif' width='498' height='200' alt='description' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>I need to practice Mindfulness or some other thingamajig to control my emotions here, but good god what did I just read? And did 9000+ human&apos;s actually give this 5 stars. <br/><br/><img src='https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1483482162ra/21617069.gif' width='250' height='300' alt='description' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/> <br/><br/>Let&apos;s start with the plot points that didn&apos;t make me want to murder someone, preferably myself so I didn&apos;t have to read any more. We start with Jason Douche-in-Chief behaving like a grade A asshole to his wife, but loves his son and heir apparent. We&apos;re meant to love him becauase his wife tup&apos;s Fre</span>
  <span id="freeText16638354384764850560" style="display:none">Okay. Okay. You can do this. <br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1525630344ra/25491513.gif" width="498" height="200" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>I need to practice Mindfulness or some other thingamajig to control my emotions here, but good god what did I just read? And did 9000+ human's actually give this 5 stars. <br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1483482162ra/21617069.gif" width="250" height="300" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"> <br><br>Let's start with the plot points that didn't make me want to murder someone, preferably myself so I didn't have to read any more. We start with Jason Douche-in-Chief behaving like a grade A asshole to his wife, but loves his son and heir apparent. We're meant to love him becauase his wife tup's French dudes and ignores their son but he loves that little boy with all his heart. <i> Totes Adorbs! </i> <br><br>Then we suddenly move to America? Canada? Who the fuck knows. Who the fuck <i> cares </i>. Here we meet our heroine Victoria who overhears her mother pleading her father to not tup her, because he promised he wouldn't after their daughter was born. Okay, sure. This made me raise my brows, but oh sweet summer child, just <i> wait </i>. Her father was all but trying to force himself on his wife who resisted, begged and then ran away and we're meant to like him and love the cozy, cute relationship Victoria has with her father? <br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1525630344ra/25491512.gif" width="498" height="280" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Yeah this is where this book lost me. But still I continued, because of this book has an average rating of 4.21 with 20k+ ratings so there must be something reedming right? RIGHT? <br><br>Some loose nonsensical plot points later, Victoria and Dorothy are newly orphaned and shipped off to England to their aristocrat familes who are planning their weddings, because why not? Our MC's have their first meeting and we're supposed to think it's endearing how rude and crude he is but this slip of a woman will change him. Yeah okay. He's a douche, but not in the usual way books like this portray rakes - they're incorrigible, make flirty comments, don't care about anything but they aren't disgusting. <br><br>Let me introdude you to Mr Jason Feilding. If I could ever whack a literary character over the head, he'd be in that list. <br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1525630344ra/25491511.gif" width="498" height="282" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>They're bethroed but she's kept in the dark for a while but then not - I won't bore you with the plot because it's thin, circles on and on endlessly and quite honestly I don't want to revisit it. <br><br>Let's get to the crux of the matter. There is constant, physical, emotional, verbal and sexual abuse by the rake we're meant to be swooning over that just somehow get's ignored by everyone, even the readers. He forces her to kiss him, then calls her his property, manhadles her often and many times you're left with the words <i>" He turned his heel and stalked out of the room, leaving her shaking with fear" </i>and it's supposed to make your insides melt from the romance? Ugh. No. <br><br>The fact that this kind of behaviour is meant to showcase passion that is meant to inspire longing in readers sickens me. This is not love, this is not passion and if you find someone like this run as fast as you can in the opposite direction. <br><br>Now let's get to the rape. Oh yes, you heard me right. Rape. On their wedding night! How romantic right? <br><br><blockquote> Visions of blood and terrible pain roared through Victoria, adding their horror to the nausea the wine was causing. "I don't want to!" she cried piteously. <br>"We made a bargain, and as long as we're married, you'll keep it," he whispered as he pried her stiff thighs apart. Victoria whimpered as his rigid manhood probed boldly at her, but somewhere in the depths of her stricken mind, she knew he was right about the bargain and she stopped fighting him(*). "Relax," he warned bitterly in the darkness above her, "I may not be as considerate as your dear Andrew, but I don't want to hurt you."<br>His vicious mention of Andrew at a time like this cut her to the heart, and her anguish erupted in a scream of pain as Jason rammed into her. Her body writhed beneath his, and tears poured from her eyes in hot, humiliated streaks as her husband used her without kindness or caring." </blockquote><br>Worst part is, not only are we treated to an asshole who abuses and rapes his wife, there's also a wonderful addition of good old victim blaming. Victoria starts to think that her fiance/husband will think less of her because she let him kiss her. <br><br>Take that in.<br><br>He will <b> think </b> less of her. <br>Because she <b> LET</b> him kiss her. <br><br>FF's that rat bastard forced you. <br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1525630344ra/25491514.gif" width="498" height="250" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>As their relationship moves forward we come to know how Victoria thinks of his treatment, and finally she starts to think it isn't right. Until of course, someone always comes into the picture to tell her how broken he is, and how he needs her and her vagina to be able to heal himself and be the best he can be. Puke. <br><br>Can we stop with the trope of women healing men with sex? Or men who only become half decent human beings because of a woman? <br><br>Jason not only cheats on her while they're engaged, but he also keeps his mistress after their marraige. But that's A-okay. Because he has needs, so it's either rape his wife or bed his mistress. I actually applaud him for this choice. <br><br>This is listed as a Romance. <br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1525630344ra/25491510.gif" width="498" height="234" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>We're meant to swoon at the hero, and his evilness that eventually becomes less evil because he's in love with a simple, extraordinary, virginal girl. No we're not. <br><br>I loathe to think of what my reaction would have been if I'd read this at 17 or 18 where all I wanted was a storybook romance. Now I'm old enough to understand when someone's a lovable jerk and a criminal. But I shudder to think of young impressionable girls reading this and thinking that Jason is the kind of man they need, want and deserve. <br><br>And to get him, they musn't be like the other women portrayed in the book - crude, manipulative and always throwing themselves as Jason's feet. They made it sound like women just instantly spread their legs when he walks into a room. But we're told that it's not these loose, virtue-less women a hero like Jason will fall in love with. No it's the pure, sweet and innocent Victoria's who get the Jason's. <br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1525630344ra/25491516.gif" width="498" height="234" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Just don't read this.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16638354384764850560" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


